  "prompt": "What was the Watergate scandal about?",
  "response": "The Watergate scandal was a major political scandal in the United States during the early 1970s, which ultimately led to the resignation of President Richard Nixon in 1974. It began with a break-in at the Democratic National Committee (DNC) headquarters at the Watergate office complex in Washington, D.C. in June 1972.\n\nKey points of the scandal include:\n\n1. Five men were caught breaking into the DNC offices, attempting to wiretap phones and steal documents.\n\n2. Investigation revealed that the break-in was connected to Nixon's re-election campaign.\n\n3. Nixon and his administration attempted to cover up their involvement in the break-in and subsequent illegal activities.\n\n4. Investigative reporting by Washington Post journalists Bob Woodward and Carl Bernstein helped expose the scandal.\n\n5. Congressional hearings and investigations uncovered evidence of abuse of presidential power, including:\n- Illegal surveillance\n- Campaign finance violations\n- Obstruction of justice\n\n6. Nixon was implicated in the cover-up and faced potential impeachment.\n\n7. On August 9, 1974, Nixon became the first U.S. president to resign from office.\n\nThe Watergate scandal significantly damaged public trust in the government and led to reforms in campaign finance and presidential powers.",
